, the support that Maker holders will get to make those decisions and the voting process to follow to manage the risk function. It is the objective of this series to gain an understanding of the risk management function and the contribution Maker token holders make in managing it.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"h2\",null,\"Stablecoins\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Stablecoins are crypto-assets that aim to maintain value relative to a specific asset or basket of assets.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"The stability implied in the name is created through a mechanism of dynamics that attempt to keep the value of the token steady with some given reference point. \"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"In most instances, that reference point is the United States dollar but could be extended to any other asset (Euro) or index (CPI).\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"h3\",null,\"Types of Stablecoins\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Currently, three mechanisms or types of stablecoin have transpired that attempt to implement this:\"),Object(o.mdx)(r,{mdxType:\"List\"},Object(o.mdx)(c,{mdxType:\"Box\"},Object(o.mdx)(\"h4\",null,\"IOU\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"The IOU organization is asking the user to place their trust in the traditional centralized system;give them an asset (usually a $1), they will keep it with a centralized custodian and will provide you with a token in return. If you want your asset back, give them the token and the centralized custodian will give you your asset back. The user explicitly trusts that the custodian will look after its assets.\")),Object(o.mdx)(c,{mdxType:\"Box\"},Object(o.mdx)(\"h4\",null,\"Seigniorage Shares\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Seigniorage share or Algorithm-based stablecoin solutions ask the user to place their trust with them. If the price of the token is too high, they will increase the supply and reduce demand. If the price is too low, they will increase demand and lower supply. The user explicitly trusts that they, or the mechanisms deployed by the organization, will respond in a timely and appropriate fashion to keep the system and by definition their token stable.\")),Object(o.mdx)(c,{mdxType:\"Box\"},Object(o.mdx)(\"h4\",null,\"Collateralized\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Collateralized organizations ask the user to place their trust in the value created by the blockchain. If the user believes that the economy of the blockchain will flourish then so will the tokens on the blockchain. Those tokens are then used to collateralize the supply of stable coin into that economy. Regardless of the governing dynamics used for stability, users place their trust first and foremost into the pledged collateral before anything else.\"))),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"The most significant difference between these solutions is where you place your trust as a user and, by extension, how you define the character of that stablecoin.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"h3\",null,\"Dai - A Collateralized Stablecoin\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Maker allows users to place their trust in distributed ledger technology through the value proposition of the Dai stablecoin. \"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Dai is supplied to the Ethereum blockchain economy by way of a lending mechanism, whereby a user borrows Dai and increases supply through on-chain transactions. \"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"To facilitate this lending, Maker has created a smart contract called a Collateralized Debt Position (CDP). \"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"The purpose of the CDP is two-fold; to accept pledged collateral tokens and to make a Dai credit facility available. Put another way, it provides loans and attempts to mitigate credit risk at the same time.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"h4\",null,\"Collateralized Debt Position - The Engine of Supply\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"A Collateralized Debt Position (CDP) is a smart contract designed to minimize credit risk and facilitate collateralization.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Credit or counterparty risk is the risk that a borrower will default on their debt. To mitigate the risk associated with borrowers defaulting, lenders ask for recourse in the form of collateral to be paid before borrowing money.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Collateralization is a fundamental tool used throughout the traditional finance space to minimize or mitigate credit risk. Collateralization occurs when a borrower pledges an asset as recourse to the lender in the event of default on that loan.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"h4\",null,\"Pledge-of-Assets and Event-of-Default\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"A CDP encapsulates these two ideas and turns the fundamental notion of a credit facility into a Dai supplying mechanism.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Assets pledged as collateral need to be unencumbered and accessible to the lender, meaning the lender can take possession and store the collateral somewhere in the event it needs to be seized. \"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"There is an industry dedicated to this process of pledging assets, ensuring they remain unencumbered, and warehousing them appropriately. This is all done in almost an instant with a CDP.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,'Defining \"Event-of-Default,\" recognizing when it happens, and taking the appropriate action is again an industry in the traditional space. The CDP makes this a well established and almost instant event to which we can identify and react.'),Object(o.mdx)(\"h2\",null,\"Governance and Decentralized Risk Management\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"What assets do we use as collateral and how do we define a default event?\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Ultimately, we would like to answer these questions through a myriad of competing risk constructs from a multitude of risk teams.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"The combination of these teams through competition and cooperative structures, which forms the basis for the Decentralized Risk Management function.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"h3\",null,\"The Goal of Risk Governance\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"The goal of governance is to establish the most effective way to protect the integrity and stability of the Maker system.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"The community is initially being guided by the \",Object(o.mdx)(\"a\",Object.assign({parentName:\"p\"},{href:\"/learn/MakerDAO/maker-foundation/\"}),\"Maker Foundation\"),\" and will eventually be led by a multitude of formally-elected risk teams and independent, volunteer risk researchers.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"A decentralized risk function’s value lies in its ability to protect against biases and at the same time challenge the status quo and make better contributions.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"h3\",null,\"Forming a Decentralized Risk Management Function\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"The community envisions a point where the community can rigorously debate a potential risk construct applicable to the system to reach scientific consensus on what is considered the best overall risk construct for the system.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Risk teams will be able to challenge the current construct in place by way of introducing a new construct for consideration.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"If accepted, the construct will receive an initial weighting that will determine how that construct will contribute to the overall risk function.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Data should be explicitly defined and may be either exogenous or endogenous to the construct. Exogenous data may be price data or qualitative data obtained outside of the construct, where endogenous data is calculated data from within the system and again used as an input for the system.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"Consensus on the construct implies agreement on all processes and production, including the data obtained, the source of the data, and any data transformations that may occur within the construct.\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"h3\",null,\"Risk Teams and Their Contributions\"),Object(o.mdx)(\"p\",null,\"As MakerDAO's risk function becomes more decentralized, the risk teams approved by Make